observations.recommendation:
We recommended that the Municipal Mayor direct the General Services Officer - Designate to:

a.1	Conduct the physical count of PPE in accordance with the procedural guidelines enumerated in COA Circular No. 2020-006;

a.2. Classify assets that did not meet the capitalization threshold of ₱50,000.00;

a.3 	Expedite the titling of lots to establish ownership of the LGU; and

a.4	Provide costs of PPEs in the RPCPPE to aid the reconciliation of the discrepancy totaling ₱158.529 million between the FS and report.

We recommended and the Municipal Mayor agreed to direct the OIC-Municipal Accountant to:

b.1 	Prepare adjusting entry/ies to reclassify the assets that did not meet the capitalization threshold of ₱50,000.00;

b.2	Ensure that the transactions are properly classified in accordance with the prescribed Chart of Accounts for Local Government Units;

b.3	Review the subsidiary ledgers, identify those items that were mis-classified and prepare the necessary adjusting entries to correct the accounts and their balances in the books; 

b.4	Identify PPEs that have already exhausted their estimated useful life to aid Management’s decision whether these will be disposed of or continued to be used in the operations of the Municipality;

b.5	Extend effort in the identification of PPEs with beginning balances totaling ₱80.820 million that are without subsidiary ledgers and supporting schedules; and

b.6 	Record constructed PPEs initially as "Construction in Progress” with the appropriate asset classification and transfer into the proper asset account upon completion

We further recommended that Municipal Mayor initiate that the useful lives and residual values of PPE without valuation are assessed in accordance with accounting rules and regulations.

We recommended that:

Monthly Report of Fuel Consumption (MRFC) for the period January 1 to December 31, 2015 be submitted to enable the Auditor to determine the reasonableness of fuel consumption. Consequently, MCRF should be regularly prepared and submitted as required;

Officials and employees concerned refund the amount of ₱165,943.89 which is considered irregular expenditures pursuant to COA Circular No. 2012-003.

1.10 	We recommended and the Local Chief Executive agreed to direct the General Services Officer - Designate to reclassify assets that did not meet the capitalization threshold of ₱50,000.00.
1.11 We also recommended and the Local Chief Executive agreed to direct the OIC-Municipal Accountant to:
a. 	Ensure that the transactions are properly classified in accordance with the prescribed Chart of Accounts for Local Government Units;
b.	Prepare adjusting entry/ies to reclassify the assets that did not meet the capitalization threshold of ₱50,000.00;
c.	Review the subsidiary ledgers, identify those items that were mis-classified and prepare the necessary adjusting entries to correct the accounts and their balances in the books;
d.	Identify PPEs that have already exhausted their estimated useful life to aid Management’s decision whether these will be disposed of or continued to be used in the operations of the Municipality; and
e.	Extend effort in the identification of PPEs with beginning balances totaling ₱80.820 million that are without subsidiary ledgers (SLs) and supporting schedules. Relatively, hard copies of such records should be maintained as part of the data management and back-up system.

2.7 	We recommended and the Local Chief Executive agreed to direct the General Services Officer to:
a.  	Conduct the physical count of PPE in accordance with the procedural guidelines enumerated in COA Circular No. 2020-006;
b. 	Reconcile the Report on the Physical Count of Property, Plant and Equipment (RPCPPE) with that of the OIC-Municipal Accountant’s records to facilitate the identification of the discrepancies and adjustments of the errors if warranted, and for the preparation of the one-time cleansing of PPEs;
c.  	Expedite the titling of lots to establish ownership of the LGU; and
d. 	Provide costs of PPEs in the RPCPPE to aid the reconciliation of the  discrepancies between the financial statements and the inventory report.
2.8 	We also recommended and the Local Chief Executive agreed to instruct the OIC-Municipal Accountant to maintain hard copies of the PPE ledgers to avoid related data losses and lack of references during future PPE reconciliation.

We recommended and the Municipal Mayor agreed to:

Create an Inventory Team from the Offices of General Services, Accounting and end users to conduct periodic physical inventory so as to confirm the physical existence of supplies and materials on hand as well as check the reliability of accounting records;

Require the Inventory Team to prepare the periodic physical inventory report duly reconciled with the balances of the accounting records and furnish the Auditor a copy of the report;

Oblige the General Services Office to maintain stock cards for each item in stock to record all receipts and issuances of supplies and materials, as well as prepare a monthly report thereof, furnishing the Accounting Office as basis to record the supplies and materials issued in the books of accounts; and

Require the Municipal Accountant to maintain subsidiary ledgers for each type of supplies, crops and other inventory items, to record acquisition, issuance and disposal.

We recommended that:

a.	The Municipal Treasurer maintain a record showing the name of taxpayers and the amount of RPT and SET due and collectible for the year which shall be updated for each collection made;

b.	The Municipal Treasurer furnish the Municipal Accountant a duly certified copy of the list mentioned in “a” at the beginning of each year;

c.	The Municipal Accountant book the RPT and SET receivable and deferred income based on the certified list provided Municipal Treasurer; and

d.	The Municipal Accountant ensure that subsequent collections of RPT and SET are recorded in accordance with Section 20 in Chapter 3 of the NGAS for LGUs Volume I.

We recommended and the Agency Head agreed to initiate the conduct of physical count of all its PPE, whether acquired through purchase or donation, including those constructed by administration and found at station in accordance with COA Circular No. 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020, and to address the following:
Verify property, plant and equipment that were acquired in CY 2010 and below if fully depreciated;
Establish records of infrastructure assets and construction in progress;
Classify assets that did not meet the capitalization threshold of ₱15,000.00 and those that have no costs; and
Update the Acknowledgment Receipts for Equipment to identify the current accountable officers and provide necessary data such as dates of issuance by the GSO and acceptance by the accountable officers.

We recommended and the Municipal Accountant agreed to:
Review available records and reconstruct subsidiary ledger for Due from LGUs and NGOs/POs in the amount of ₱2,012,013.09 and ₱30,000.00, respectively. Otherwise, submit a request for an authority to write off accounts;
Send final demand letter for accounts due from NGOs/POs and require immediate liquidation of outstanding account balances, and;
Refrain from granting additional fund transfers to LGUs or NGOs/POs with unliquidated accounts.

We recommended that:

a.	The Municipal Treasurer maintain a record showing the name of taxpayers and the amount of RPT and SET due and collectible for the year which shall be updated for each collections made;

b.	The Municipal Treasurer furnish the Municipal Accountant a duly certified copy of the list mentioned in “a” at the beginning of each year;

c.	The Municipal Accountant book the RPT and SET receivable and deferred income based in the certified list provided Municipal Treasurer; and

d.	The Municipal Accountant ensure that subsequent collections of RPT and SET are recorded in accordance with Section 20 in Chapter 3 of the NGAS for LGUs Volume I.

Recommendations
We recommended and the Municipal Mayor agreed to:
Create an Inventory Team from the Offices of General Services, Accounting and end users to conduct periodic physical inventory so as to confirm the physical existence of supplies and materials on hand as well as check the reliability of accounting records;
Require the Inventory Team to prepare the periodic physical inventory report duly reconciled with the balances of the accounting records and furnish the Auditor a copy of the report;
Oblige the General Services Office to maintain stock cards for each item in stock to record all receipts and issuances of supplies and materials, as well as, prepare a monthly report thereof, furnishing the Accounting Office as basis to record the supplies and materials issued in the books of accounts; and
Require the Municipal Accountant to maintain subsidiary ledgers for each type of supplies, crops and other inventory items, to record acquisition, issuance and disposal.

We recommended that:

a. The Municipal Accountant transfer back to the General Fund the excess STF amounting to ₱112,936.60;

b. The Municipal Budget Officer implement additional control measures to ensure that the SAAOB issued by her officer are free from any misstatements; and

We recommended that:
The Municipal Treasurer maintain a record showing the name of taxpayers and the amount of RPT and SET due and collectible for the year which shall be updated for each collections made;
The Municipal Treasurer furnish the Municipal Accountant a duly certified copy of the list mentioned in “a” at the beginning of each year;
The Municipal Accountant book the RPT and SET receivable and deferred income based in the certified list provided Municipal Treasurer; and
The Municipal Accountant ensure that subsequent collections of RPT and SET are recorded in accordance with Section 20 in Chapter 3 of the NGAS for LGUs Volume I.

We recommended that copy of any contract, letter order, job order or purchase order, regardless of the amount, and all its supporting documents be submitted to the Auditor concerned within five (5) days from issuance. 

The copies of documents required to be submitted shall include, but not limited to the following:

Invitation to Apply for Eligibility and to Bid;
Letter of Intent;
Eligibility Documents and Eligibility Data Sheet;
Eligibility Requirements;
Results of Eligibility Checks/Screening;
Bidding Documents (Sec. 17.1 IRR and –A, R.A. 9184);
Minutes of Pre-bid Conference, if applicable;
Agenda and/or Supplemental Bid Bulletins, if any;
Bidders Technical and Financial Proposals;
Minutes of Bid Opening;
Abstract of Bids;
Post Qualification Report of Technical Working Group;
BAC Resolution declaring winning bidder;
Notice of Post Qualification;
BAC Resolution recommending approval;
Notice of Award;
Contract Agreement;
Performance Security;
Program of Work and Detailed Estimates;
Certificate of Availability of Funds, Obligation Request;
Notice to Proceed;
Such other documents peculiar to the contract and/or to the mode of procurement and considered necessary in the auditorial review and in the technical evaluation thereof.

Copies of these essential documents are necessary not only in the audit of financial transactions and the LGU’s compliance to existing laws, rules and regulations, but also in the evaluation of the effectiveness of the Municipal Government in the implementation of its programs and projects. Moreover, correction, if any, could be made at the earliest possible time once initial review and evaluation of the contract is performed.

